So anyway, Tom created this wonderful deck

00:00:03.080 --> 00:00:05.280
and I was just gonna copy it because it's a quarter deck,

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:08.000
but I figured that that wasn't right.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.360
So I'm just presenting his great slides that he built.

00:00:12.220 --> 00:00:16.879
So I'm very happy to announce that we have recently closed

00:00:16.879 --> 00:00:21.879
like the most liked issue in the RStudio IDE repo,

00:00:24.879 --> 00:00:27.559
519 votes for it,

00:00:27.559 --> 00:00:32.080
which is the request to have Copilot integrated in the IDE.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:33.799
We know that other IDEs have it

00:00:33.799 --> 00:00:35.680
and RStudio didn't have it,

00:00:35.680 --> 00:00:37.680
and we'll talk about a little why.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:40.560
So yeah, we have that now.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:42.480
So what I wanna do, I wanna talk about this

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:45.639
and how you can use it and also other alternatives

00:00:45.639 --> 00:00:48.480
to be able to use LLX, right?

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:52.360
So one of the things that I just wanna talk about real quick

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:54.919
is the famous generative AI, right?

00:00:54.919 --> 00:00:57.119
We hear that term a lot now.

00:00:57.599 --> 00:00:58.880
It feels like a big buzzword, right?

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:00.720
Just like big data was at one point.

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:05.879
But essentially what it boils down to is using models

00:01:05.879 --> 00:01:08.720
to be able to create new content, right?

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:13.040
Such as text or we can do images or videos

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:14.080
or things like that.

00:01:14.959 --> 00:01:18.320
It's something that becomes very useful,

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:20.360
especially in the development process, right?

00:01:20.360 --> 00:01:23.879
So typically we think of models as something that we use

00:01:23.879 --> 00:01:25.720
for as a product of our jobs.

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:28.320
In this case, we're consuming the model, right?

00:01:30.519 --> 00:01:35.519
So when it comes to the actual text for generative AI,

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.320
what we're talking about is that we're using it

00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:40.959
to complete something, right?

00:01:40.959 --> 00:01:45.279
So we're training the model in a way that

00:01:45.279 --> 00:01:47.879
it's able to not only predict like your next word,

00:01:47.879 --> 00:01:50.160
it's able to predict like the next sentence

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.480
or thought or paragraph, right?

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:55.599
And so if you have used ChatGPT,

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:59.080
you basically are familiar with how it does it.

00:02:00.440 --> 00:02:03.279
But unlike the autocomplete in your phone

00:02:03.279 --> 00:02:05.320
that is usually wrong,

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:07.959
something such as ChatGPT is trained

00:02:07.959 --> 00:02:10.479
with billions and billions of words

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:12.360
and how they're stringed together.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:15.679
So it's very well-educated when it comes to that.

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:19.440
So what Copilot does is that it takes those ideas, right?

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:22.520
But instead of trying to predict your next word

00:02:22.520 --> 00:02:25.199
or next paragraph that you wanna write in prose,

00:02:25.839 --> 00:02:28.279
it predicts the code that you're trying to generate, right?

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:30.320
And that's why it becomes very useful

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:33.160
because with it, then you can actually use it

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:37.080
to write your code real fast, right?

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:39.600
So we will all be in the same situation

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:41.240
where we have to write code.

00:02:41.240 --> 00:02:45.320
And we know that we're always gonna be like using the same,

00:02:46.399 --> 00:02:48.199
there's the same code that we usually copy

00:02:48.199 --> 00:02:50.479
or we have to come up with the same mechanism

00:02:50.479 --> 00:02:52.720
to do something and maybe in varied ways.

00:02:52.720 --> 00:02:54.279
Well, that's where Copilot comes in

00:02:54.279 --> 00:02:56.279
where it makes it easier for us, right?

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:01.240
Now, in RStudio, you are used to using the autocomplete,

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:02.080
right?

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:03.000
So this is a lot of words here.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:04.199
I'm just gonna go into this part

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:07.119
so to kind of for you to see as I'm talking about it.

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:11.000
So the RStudio one, we're used to

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.160
that it's gonna predict the next word.

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:15.279
In other words, like the next function,

00:03:15.279 --> 00:03:17.440
maybe the variable that you're gonna select

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:19.639
and that's it, right?

00:03:19.639 --> 00:03:24.320
And in order for you to select the autocompleted thing,

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:27.119
you use the dropdown and then select the one

00:03:27.119 --> 00:03:30.759
that you write it with your mouse or with your keyboard.

00:03:30.759 --> 00:03:33.559
The way that Copilot works is that

00:03:33.559 --> 00:03:38.559
it actually provides a sort of suggested completion, right?

00:03:39.399 --> 00:03:41.039
Very similar again to how it works

00:03:41.039 --> 00:03:43.839
with like Google Docs or your phone.

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:46.080
It actually gives you like a preview

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:47.320
of the code that could be,

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:49.279
and that's the part that we didn't have before.

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:51.960
That's called the shadow code, right?

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:54.759
So it's code that's being suggested,

00:03:54.759 --> 00:03:59.160
but it's not code that's official in your script, right?

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:00.880
So that's where it becomes really useful

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:05.539
because now with the change that in RStudio that we have,

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:09.440
that now it allows for the shadow code,

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:10.880
now we can use Copilot, right?

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:12.399
So that was the biggest thing.

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:15.160
And then here's a preview of that right now.

00:04:16.279 --> 00:04:18.720
So what's really neat is that Ghost Text

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:21.200
can go beyond just a dropdown, right?

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:23.959
Ghost Text can do multiple lines.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:28.040
And what we do is that we provide some context, right?

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:31.880
As a comment in your code that says, like example here,

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:34.119
calculate the average field efficiency of cars

00:04:34.119 --> 00:04:36.799
and then group them by the cylinder.

00:04:36.799 --> 00:04:40.600
And then the Copilot generates that.

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:42.079
You start typing library dplyr

00:04:42.079 --> 00:04:43.239
and all of a sudden Copilot says,

00:04:43.239 --> 00:04:45.399
oh, I know exactly what you're gonna write here.

00:04:45.399 --> 00:04:46.559
And then you have it, right?

00:04:46.559 --> 00:04:47.880
Then you can use it.

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:53.040
Also notice that the code itself, the shadow code,

00:04:53.040 --> 00:04:55.720
doesn't generate line six and seven in this case.

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:57.279
And that's because it's not official code,

00:04:57.279 --> 00:04:58.119
like I mentioned, right?

00:04:58.119 --> 00:05:03.119
This is just Ghost code that you can actually accept

00:05:03.119 --> 00:05:07.500
or not accept if you don't want to be part of your code.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:12.299
So here's a demo of how it looks.

00:05:12.299 --> 00:05:17.299
Notice that it says Copilot completion response received.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:20.019
So as you're writing, it's gonna be going over

00:05:20.019 --> 00:05:23.299
and hitting the API, which is the other big difference,

00:05:23.299 --> 00:05:28.019
is that with the regular dropdown autocomplete

00:05:28.019 --> 00:05:28.859
that we're used to,

00:05:28.859 --> 00:05:33.739
that's all inside the RStudio IDE installation files, right?

00:05:33.739 --> 00:05:36.299
But with Copilot, this is something

00:05:36.299 --> 00:05:38.260
that is actually going out, right?

00:05:38.260 --> 00:05:42.220
To the Copilot API and sending the code that you have

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:43.140
and the comments and all that,

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:46.380
and then sending back the request,

00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:47.980
excuse me, the responses, right?

00:05:47.980 --> 00:05:51.459
So this is something that, of course, being in pharma,

00:05:51.459 --> 00:05:54.859
that's something I'm sure that there's gonna be some things

00:05:54.859 --> 00:05:57.179
that you're gonna have to talk through

00:05:57.179 --> 00:06:00.179
within your organization to be able to use.

00:06:00.179 --> 00:06:03.739
But even in your personal life,

00:06:03.739 --> 00:06:05.459
if you're recording from home and stuff,

00:06:05.459 --> 00:06:07.959
this may be something that you can use immediately.

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:13.959
What you do today, once you upgrade your RStudio IDE,

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:19.500
you'll see on the global settings,

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:22.320
a new option at the bottom called Copilot,

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:24.600
and that's where you're gonna turn it on, right?

00:06:24.600 --> 00:06:28.679
You start the process, and then it'll walk you

00:06:28.679 --> 00:06:33.320
through getting the token from GitHub,

00:06:33.320 --> 00:06:36.480
and then you'll be able to use it, right?

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:38.839
So that's what you will have to use

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:41.880
in order to get it to work.

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:51.399
So here, what Tom was wanting to show

00:06:51.399 --> 00:06:56.399
is how we can use it to create a quick game-solving code,

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:02.320
and that you can be using very specific

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:04.519
and simple comments can get you there.

00:07:04.519 --> 00:07:07.559
So what we want is to be able to,

00:07:07.559 --> 00:07:11.760
for it to create a few functions that would solve a game,

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:16.559
and that's whenever there's multiple little words like this,

00:07:16.559 --> 00:07:19.239
like what is the word that is supposed

00:07:19.239 --> 00:07:21.799
to be across all these words, right?

00:07:21.799 --> 00:07:25.480
So he takes the example here of the actual answers,

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:28.079
but what we want is for it to actually give me the,

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:30.559
for it to solve it for me.

00:07:30.559 --> 00:07:33.480
So you'll notice here, I start by getting

00:07:33.799 --> 00:07:37.720
the latest for today of whatever date I want to put in.

00:07:37.720 --> 00:07:41.279
He puts all these comments in order to get it right, right?

00:07:41.279 --> 00:07:43.440
So it's gonna download, excuse me,

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:46.760
yeah, it's gonna download the proper date

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:51.279
for that day's puzzle, and it's gonna replace it

00:07:51.279 --> 00:07:53.839
with dashes instead of forward slashes,

00:07:53.839 --> 00:07:56.239
and create the URL that I need

00:07:56.239 --> 00:08:00.160
in order to download the latest file, right?

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:02.880
I think I'm running out of time here.

00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:08.440
So then we can see how Tom used it here

00:08:11.799 --> 00:08:16.799
to create the actual functions that will find

00:08:19.959 --> 00:08:23.519
and replace through dredgex the underscores

00:08:23.519 --> 00:08:28.480
based on the words that are like your hint words, right?

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:30.000
But notice that all he's doing

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:33.559
is just adding the comments, right?

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:38.119
And those comments serve as a prompt for Copilot to use.

00:08:38.119 --> 00:08:40.119
And of course, we're gonna share the link to this

00:08:40.119 --> 00:08:43.440
so you can see we also have the entire document

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:46.080
that you can recreate if you want to.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:49.000
And then he used it to create all of it

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.520
all the way down to where you can start

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:54.760
with just guess word and you put in the date

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:58.840
and that will pick up the clues and come up with responses.

00:08:58.840 --> 00:09:01.719
In this case, you notice that the program

00:09:01.719 --> 00:09:05.719
that was 99.99% created by Copilot

00:09:09.159 --> 00:09:10.719
is working with no problems.

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:14.239
Let me...

00:09:15.799 --> 00:09:17.679
Are they running out of time?

